Exercise 2¶

2.1¶

Given the function

ϕ~(x,t)=14πDt−−−−√exp(−(x−μ)24Dt),ϕ~(x,t)=14πDtexp(−(x−μ)24Dt),

its partial derivatives are

∂ϕ~∂t=−ϕ~(12t−(x−μ)24Dt2),∂ϕ~∂x=ϕ~−(x−μ)2Dt,∂2ϕ~∂2x=−ϕ~(12Dt−(x−μ)24D2t2)=1D∂ϕ~∂t,∂ϕ~∂t=−ϕ~(12t−(x−μ)24Dt2),∂ϕ~∂x=ϕ~−(x−μ)2Dt,∂2ϕ~∂2x=−ϕ~(12Dt−(x−μ)24D2t2)=1D∂ϕ~∂t,

and the function satisfies the diffusion equation

∂ϕ~(x,t)∂t=D∂2ϕ~(x,t)∂x2∂ϕ~(x,t)∂t=D∂2ϕ~(x,t)∂x2

2.2.1¶

Let

ϕ(x,0)=δ(x−x0)=12π∫∞−∞exp(−ik(x−x0))dkϕ(x,0)=δ(x−x0)=12π∫−∞∞exp⁡(−ik(x−x0))dk

be a particle distribuition in 1D at time t=0t=0, and assume that it follows the diffusion equation. Differentiating this with respect to xx yields

∂ϕ∂x=∂∂x12π∫∞−∞exp(−ik(x−x0))dk=12π∫∞−∞−ikexp(−ik(x−x0))dk,∂2ϕ∂x2=12π∫∞−∞−k2exp(−ik(x−x0))dk.∂ϕ∂x=∂∂x12π∫−∞∞exp⁡(−ik(x−x0))dk=12π∫−∞∞−ikexp⁡(−ik(x−x0))dk,∂2ϕ∂x2=12π∫−∞∞−k2exp⁡(−ik(x−x0))dk.

The time derivative at time t=0t=0 is then given by

∂ϕ∂t∣∣t=0=12π∫∞−∞−Dk2exp(−ik(x−x0))dk∂ϕ∂t|t=0=12π∫−∞∞−Dk2exp⁡(−ik(x−x0))dk

To find the nnth time derivative, one can use the taylor expansion of ϕ(x,t)ϕ(x,t) at t=0t=0 given by

ϕ(x,t)=ϕ(x,0)+∑n=1∞tnn!∂nϕ(x,τ)∂τn∣∣∣τ=0.ϕ(x,t)=ϕ(x,0)+∑n=1∞tnn!∂nϕ(x,τ)∂τn|τ=0.

Substituting this into the diffusion equation yields

D∂2ϕ∂x2=D∑n=0∞tnn!∂2∂x2(∂nϕ(x,τ)∂τn)∣∣∣τ=0=∂ϕ∂t=∑n=1∞ntn−1n!∂n∂τn(ϕ(x,τ))∣∣∣τ=0=∑n=0∞tnn!∂n+1∂τn+1(ϕ(x,τ))∣∣∣τ=0D∂2ϕ∂x2=D∑n=0∞tnn!∂2∂x2(∂nϕ(x,τ)∂τn)|τ=0=∂ϕ∂t=∑n=1∞ntn−1n!∂n∂τn(ϕ(x,τ))|τ=0=∑n=0∞tnn!∂n+1∂τn+1(ϕ(x,τ))|τ=0

The uniqueness of Taylor-sereis then gives that

D∂2∂x2(∂nϕ(x,τ)∂τn)∣∣∣τ=0=∂n+1ϕ(x,τ)∂τn+1∣∣∣τ=0,∀n∈N.D∂2∂x2(∂nϕ(x,τ)∂τn)|τ=0=∂n+1ϕ(x,τ)∂τn+1|τ=0,∀n∈N.

This gives a recursice formula for the derivative with respec to to tt at t=0t=0, and can be used to evaluate the nnth derivatie,

∂nϕ(x,τ)∂τn∣∣∣τ=0=D∂2∂x2∂n−1ϕ(x,τ)∂τn−1∣∣∣τ=0=…=Dn∂2nϕ(x,τ)∂x2n∣∣∣τ=0=12π∫∞−∞(−Dk2)nexp(−ik(x−x0))dk,∂nϕ(x,τ)∂τn|τ=0=D∂2∂x2∂n−1ϕ(x,τ)∂τn−1|τ=0=…=Dn∂2nϕ(x,τ)∂x2n|τ=0=12π∫−∞∞(−Dk2)nexp⁡(−ik(x−x0))dk,

which means the taylor expansion can be written

ϕ(x,t)=ϕ(x,0)+∑n=1∞tnn!12π∫∞−∞(−k2D)nexp((x−x0))dk=12π∫∞−∞∑n=0∞(−k2Dt)nn!exp(−ik(x−x0))dk=12π∫∞−∞exp(−k2Dt)exp(−ik(x−x0))dk.ϕ(x,t)=ϕ(x,0)+∑n=1∞tnn!12π∫−∞∞(−k2D)nexp⁡((x−x0))dk=12π∫−∞∞∑n=0∞(−k2Dt)nn!exp⁡(−ik(x−x0))dk=12π∫−∞∞exp⁡(−k2Dt)exp⁡(−ik(x−x0))dk.

ϕ(x,t)ϕ(x,t) is, down to a multiplicative constant, the fourier transform, f^(x−x0,t)f^(x−x0,t), of f(k,t)=exp(−Dtk2)f(k,t)=exp⁡(−Dtk2). By noticing that ∂kf(k,t)=−2Dtkf(k,t)∂kf(k,t)=−2Dtkf(k,t), and taking the fourier transform of both sides,

Fk[∂kf(k,t)](x−x0)=∫∞−∞∂kf(k)exp(−ik(x−x0))dk=[f(k)exp(−ik(x−x0))+i(x−x0)∫f(k)exp(−ik(x−x0))dk]k=∞k=−∞=i(x−x0)f^(x−x0,t)Fk[∂kf(k,t)](x−x0)=∫−∞∞∂kf(k)exp(−ik(x−x0))dk=[f(k)exp(−ik(x−x0))+i(x−x0)∫f(k)exp(−ik(x−x0))dk]k=−∞k=∞=i(x−x0)f^(x−x0,t)



Fk[−2Dtkf(k)]=−2Dt∫∞−∞kf(k)exp(−ik(x−x0))dk=−i2Dt∂x∫∞−∞f(k)exp(−ik(x−x0))dk=−i2Dt∂xf^(x−x0,t),Fk[−2Dtkf(k)]=−2Dt∫−∞∞kf(k)exp(−ik(x−x0))dk=−i2Dt∂x∫−∞∞f(k)exp(−ik(x−x0))dk=−i2Dt∂xf^(x−x0,t),

one sees that the equation for f^(x−x0,t)f^(x−x0,t), and by extention ϕ(x,t)ϕ(x,t), is given by

(x−x0)f^(x−x0,t)+2Dt∂xf^(x−x0,t)=0,(x−x0)f^(x−x0,t)+2Dt∂xf^(x−x0,t)=0,

The genereal solution is

xy=C1dydx∫xC1dx=∫1ydyy(x)=C2exp(x22C1),xy=C1dydx∫xC1dx=∫1ydyy(x)=C2exp⁡(x22C1),

which in this case gives

ϕ(x,t)=12π∫∞−∞exp(−k2Dt)exp(−ik(x−x0))dk=C1(t)exp(−(x−x0)24Dt)ϕ(x,t)=12π∫−∞∞exp⁡(−k2Dt)exp⁡(−ik(x−x0))dk=C1(t)exp⁡(−(x−x0)24Dt)

C1(t)C1(t) is found by normalizing, as

∫Rϕ(x,0)dx=1=∫RC1(t)exp(−(x−x0)24Dt)dx=C1(t)4πDt−−−−√,∫Rϕ(x,0)dx=1=∫RC1(t)exp⁡(−(x−x0)24Dt)dx=C1(t)4πDt,

the time dependent distribution becomes

ϕ(x,t)=14πDt−−−−√exp(−(x−x0)24Dt)ϕ(x,t)=14πDtexp⁡(−(x−x0)24Dt)

2.2.2¶

The diffusion constant DD gives the relationship between the curvature and the time-derivative. That is, the larger the value of DD, the faster a peak or valley in the distribution flattens, as those are the places where ϕ′′(x)ϕ″(x) has its maximum absolute values. The flattening of a peak in the diffusion equation corresponds to particles spreading out from a starting distribution.

2.2.3¶

Assuming an arbitrary, normalized and square integrable starting distribution

ϕ(x,0)=g(x),ϕ(x,0)=g(x),

the time evolution can be found by taking the fourier transform of the diffusion equation,

∂∂tϕ^(ω,t)=−ω2Dϕ^(ω,t)⟹ϕ^=C(ω)exp(−ω2Dt)∂∂tϕ^(ω,t)=−ω2Dϕ^(ω,t)⟹ϕ^=C(ω)exp⁡(−ω2Dt)

seeing that

g(x)=F−1[ϕ^(ω,0)]=F−1[C(ω)]⟹C(ω)=g^(ω),g(x)=F−1[ϕ^(ω,0)]=F−1[C(ω)]⟹C(ω)=g^(ω),

the time dependent solution is given by

ϕ(x,t)=∫Rg^(ω)exp(−ω2Dt)exp(iωx)dω=∫R∫Rg(k)exp(ikω)dkexp(−ω2Dt)exp(−iωx)dω=∫Rg(k)∫Rexp(−ω2Dt)exp(−iω(x−k))dωdk=14πDt−−−−√∫Rg(k)exp(−(x−k)24Dt)dk.ϕ(x,t)=∫Rg^(ω)exp⁡(−ω2Dt)exp⁡(iωx)dω=∫R∫Rg(k)exp⁡(ikω)dkexp⁡(−ω2Dt)exp⁡(−iωx)dω=∫Rg(k)∫Rexp⁡(−ω2Dt)exp⁡(−iω(x−k))dωdk=14πDt∫Rg(k)exp⁡(−(x−k)24Dt)dk.

This agrees with the results from befroe, seeing as substituting g(x)=δ(x−x0)g(x)=δ(x−x0) yields

14πDt−−−−√∫Rδ(k−x0)exp(−(x−k)24Dt)dk=14πDt−−−−√exp(−(x−x0)24Dt)14πDt∫Rδ(k−x0)exp⁡(−(x−k)24Dt)dk=14πDtexp⁡(−(x−x0)24Dt)

# Different potentials. Takes a x-value and the step length as arguments, 
# and returns the potential in this point. 

def V0(x, h):
    return 0

def V1(x, h):
    return x

def V2(x, h):
    if x < 3 * h and x > -3*h:
        return 1;
    else:
        return 0;
    
def V3(x, h):
    if x < -3 * h:
        return -1
    elif x > 3 * h:
        return 1
    return -1 + 2 * (x + 3 * h) / (6 * h)

# This function simulates random walk in 1D, with an arbitary potential V as input parameter. 
# Other parameters:
# N: number of particle, t: number of time steps, L: length of x - axis in the plot  
# h: step length, betaK: the constant beta * k (ratio between potential and thermal energy)  

def randomWalk(V, N, t, h, betaK = 1):
        points = np.zeros(N)
        
        for i in range(N):
            pos = 0
            for j in range(t):
                randNum = random.random()
                P_pluss = 1/(1 + np.exp(-betaK * (V(pos - h, h) - V(pos + h, h))))
                if randNum < P_pluss:
                    pos += 1
                else:
                    pos -= 1            
            points[i] += pos
        
        return points

# Find values to represent a normal curve that fits to the histogram.
def normalCurveFit(ax, xAx, points, N):
   
    # mu: expectation value, std: standard deviation
    mu, std = norm.fit(points)
    # Make the normalized normal curve
    p = norm.pdf(xAx, mu, std)
    ax2 = ax.twinx()
    ax.set_ylim(0, 2 * N / (sqrt(2 * pi) * std) * 1.2)
    ax2.set_ylim(0, 1 / (sqrt(2 * pi) * std) * 1.2)
    ax2.set_ylabel("Probability density")
    ax2.plot(xAx, p, linewidth=2, color = "red", label = "Probability density")
    return ax2

# Plots the potential
def plotPotential(ax, xAx, V, h):
    vList = np.array([V(x, h) for x in xAx])
    ax2 = ax.twinx()
    ax2.plot(xAx, vList, "--k", label = "$V(x)$")
    ax2.set_ylabel("Potential [$\\beta k$]")
    return ax2

# Plots the distibution of particles
def plotDist(ax, points, betaK, N, V, h, title = ""):
    xMax = np.max(np.abs([np.min(points), np.max(points)]))
    xRange = (-xMax * 1.1, xMax * 1.1)
    xAx = np.linspace(*xRange, 100)

    ax.hist(points, range = xRange, bins = 100, label = "Number of paricles")
    ax.set_xlim(*xRange)
    ax.set_xlabel("Position")
    ax.set_ylabel("Number of paricles")

    return ax, xAx

# Plot for exercice 3 and 5
def plotRandomWalk(numPlots, V, nCols = 2, curveFit = False, N = 1000, figNo = 0):
    
    betaKValues = np.linspace(0.1, 10, numPlots)
    nRows = numPlots // nCols + numPlots % nCols

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(nRows, nCols, figsize = (18, 6 * nRows))
    if (figNo):
        fig.suptitle("fig. " + str(figNo))
        
    # The code expects a double array, which subplots only returns if nCols, nRows > 1
    if nCols == 1:
        axs = np.array([axs,])
    if nRows == 1:
        axs = np.array([axs,])
        
    t, h = 100, 1
    
    for i in range(nRows):
        for j in range(nCols):
            
            if numPlots % nCols and j >= numPlots % nCols and i == nRows - 1:
                ax[i, j].axis("off")
                continue
                
            betaK = betaKValues[j + nCols * i]
            points = randomWalk(V, N, t, h, betaK)
            ax, xAx = plotDist(axs[i, j], points, betaK, N, V, h)
            ax.set_title("$\\beta k$ =  " + "{:.2f}".format(betaK))
            handles, legends = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()
            
            if curveFit:
                ax2 = normalCurveFit(ax, xAx, points, N)
            else: 
                ax2 = plotPotential(ax, xAx, V, h)
                
            hs, ls = ax2.get_legend_handles_labels()
            handles.extend(hs) 
            legends.extend(ls)
            
    plt.subplots_adjust(hspace = 0.3, wspace = 0.45)
    axs[0, nCols - 1].legend(handles, legends, loc = "upper right")
    
    plt.show()

Explanation of exercise 3¶

There is a binary choice between going to the right or to the left every step in the random walk, with probability P+P+ and P−P−, respectivley. The potential (meaning the potential energy) is constant, cauising the probabilities to remain equal and constant, making every iteration a bernoulli process. This means the probaility density of the distribution with constant potential is a binomial distribution b(x;n,P+)=(nx)(P+)x(1−P+)n−xb(x;n,P+)=(nx)(P+)x(1−P+)n−x. The normal distribution is the limit of the binomial distribution as nn goes to infinity, explaining why the data fits the normal curve, as shown in figure 1.

Discussion of results from Exercise 5.¶

The ratio βk=k/TkBβk=k/TkB, where TT is the temperature of the system, kBkB is the Boltzmann constant, and kk is a constant characterizing the strength of the potenial, is a measure of the ratio between the thermal energy of the system and the potential the particles move in. Since random movement and consequently diffusion is driven by thermal energy, the impact of the potential becomes more and more apparent with increasing values of βkβk. For the lower values of βkβk the distribution of particles is close to a normal distribution centered in the origin, similar to the case with a constant potential. For higher values of βkβk the distribution of particles is skewed towards the areas with lower potential.

# Functions used in randomWalkCell

# Function that returns the potential, given an x value, the width of the membrane (2h), 
# the time-dependent potential Vt and the constant potential corresponing to the specific ion in
def VTot(x, h, Vt, VCons, L):
    func = np.array([np.inf, Vt, lambda x: -Vt *(x-h) / (2*h) + VCons, 0])
    conditions = np.array([np.logical_or((x < -L / 2), (x > L / 2)), 
                           np.logical_and((x > -L / 2), (x < -h)),
                           np.logical_and((x > -h), (x < h)), 
                           np.logical_and((x > h), (x < L / 2))])
    return np.piecewise(x, conditions, func)

# Executes one time step of the random walk
def Step(pos, h, Vt, betaVC, L):
    randArr = np.random.rand(pos.size)
    arg = - (VTot(pos - h, h, Vt, betaVC, L) - VTot(pos + h, h, Vt, betaVC, L))
    P_plussArr = 1/(1 + np.exp(arg))
    # Creates an array with 1 if the elemet is > 0, 0 otherwise
    stepArr = ((P_plussArr - randArr) > 0)
    return pos + stepArr * h + (stepArr - np.ones(stepArr.size)) * h

# Function that handles the action potential. Swiches the potentials of sodium and potassium 
# when the voltage V(t) reaches treshold values.
def gateSwitch(betaVt, treshLow, treshHigh, betaVCK, betaVCNa, betaVOpen, betaVClosed):
    if betaVt <= treshLow :
        betaVCK = betaVClosed
        betaVCNa = betaVOpen
    if betaVt >= treshHigh:
        betaVCK = betaVOpen
        betaVCNa = betaVClosed
    return betaVCK, betaVCNa

# Function that executes the particle transportation from the SSP. 
def SSP(posK, posNa, h):
    N_K = np.count_nonzero(posK > h)
    N_Na = np.count_nonzero(posNa < -h)
    if N_K >= 2 and N_Na >= 3:
        posK.sort()
        posNa.sort()
        
        i_K = np.argmax(posK > h)
        for n in range(2):
            posK[i_K + n] = -2.5 * h
            
        i_Na = np.argmax(posNa > -2*h) - 1
        for n in range(3):
            posNa[i_Na - n] = 2.5 * h

# Runs the random walk, with or without a SSP and action potential
def randomWalkCell(startPos, NKEnv, NNaEnv, NKCell, NNaCell, betaVK, betaVNa,t, pump = True, action = True):
    posK = np.concatenate((np.ones(NKEnv) * startPos, np.ones(NKCell) * (-startPos)), axis = 0)
    posNa = np.concatenate((np.ones(NNaEnv) * startPos, np.ones(NNaCell) * (-startPos)), axis = 0)
    
    VtArr = np.zeros(t)
    tArr = np.arange(t)
    
    for i in range(t):
        if pump and i % 10 == 0:
            SSP(posK, posNa, h)
        
        consK = np.count_nonzero(posK < -h) * 1e-4
        consNa = np.count_nonzero(posNa < -h) * 1e-4
        betaVt = -(150e-3 - (consK + consNa)) * e / (k_B * 310) / Cc  
        VtArr[i] = betaVt
        
        if action:
            betaVK, betaVNa = gateSwitch(betaVt, treshLow, treshHigh, betaVK, betaVNa, betaVOpen, betaVClosed)
        posK = Step(posK, h, betaVt, betaVK, L)
        posNa = Step(posNa, h, betaVt, betaVNa, L)
        
    return posK, posNa, tArr, VtArr

# Plots the particle distribution
def plotPos(ax, pos, legend):
    xMax = np.max(np.abs([np.min(pos), np.max(pos)]))
    xRange = (-xMax * 1, xMax * 1)
    ax.hist(pos, range = xRange, bins = 100, alpha = 0.7, label = legend)
    ax.set_xlim(*xRange)
    ax.set_xlabel("Postition")
    ax.set_ylabel("$N$, number of paricles")
    return ax

# Plots the voltage over the mebrane as function of time
def plotVoltage(ax, V, t, lineType):
    ax.plot(V, t, lineType, label = "$V(t)$")
    ax.set_xlabel("t")
    ax.set_ylabel("Voltage [$\\beta e$]")
    ax.set_ylim((-3.5, 2))    
    ax2 = ax.twinx()
    ax2.set_ylim(np.array(ax.get_ylim()) / ebeta)
    ax2.set_ylabel("Voltage [V]")
    return ax, ax2

# Smooths the function to show trends, by taking average values. Plots this curve. 
def plotVSmooth(ax, t, V, n):
    Vs = np.zeros_like(V)
    Vs[0] += V[0]
    Vs[-1] += V[-1]
    for i in range(1, len(V) - 1):
        if i < n:
            Vs[i] = np.sum(V[:2 * i]) / (2 * i)
        elif i > len(V) - n:
            Vs[i] = np.sum(V[-2 * (len(V) - i): -1]) / (2 * (len(V) - i) - 1)
        else: 
            Vs[i] = np.sum(V[i - n: i + n]) / (2 * n)
    legend = "Average of $2 \cdot" + str(n) + " + 1$ values"
    ax.plot(t, Vs, "--r", linewidth = 3, label = legend)
    return ax

# Plots both the distribution and potential in one figure
def plotRWCell(posK, posNa, tArr, VtArr, betaV0K, betaV0Na, figNo = 0, smooth = True, lineType = "."):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize = (18, 6))
    ax[0] = plotPos(ax[0], posK, "$K$")
    ax[0] = plotPos(ax[0], posNa, "$Na$")
    ax[0].legend()
    
    ax[1], _ = plotVoltage(ax[1], tArr, VtArr, lineType)
    if smooth:
        ax[1] = plotVSmooth(ax[1], tArr, VtArr, 10)
    title = ""
    ax[1].legend()
    
    if figNo:
        title += "fig. " + str(figNo) + "\n"
    
    title += "$\\beta V^0_{K} = " + str(betaV0K) + "\quad"\
        + "\\beta V^0_{Na}=" + str(betaV0Na) + "$\n" 
    
    fig.suptitle(title, y = 1.02)
    plt.show()

Discussion of results from 7.1¶

Figures 5, 6 and 7 show the distribution of the sodium and potassium ions after a random walk of 500500 time steps in a potential, as well as the voltage V(t)V(t) over the membrane plotted against the time steps. This is done for βk∈{0,1,3}βk∈{0,1,3}. The simiulation starts with 50 sodium ions and 1400 potassium ions inside the cell, and 50 potassium ions and 1450 sodium ions in the enviroment. Each particle represents a concentration of 0.1mM0.1mM. This starting concentration is used in the rest of the exercises.

The voltage V(t)≠0V(t)≠0 results in a net electric force and therefore a net charge flow. Since the membrane potential is low for both sodium and potassium, the ions can travel across the barrier with a non- negligible probability, and make the voltage settle around zero. When the voltage reaches zero the total particle concentration on each side will be aproximately equal, making the diffusion effect negligible compared the electric force. Therfore diffusion wil not push the voltage away from zero. With time, the diffusion will exchange potassium and sodium ions causing the sodium and potassium concentrations to be equal without changing the total concentration.

As expected, the voltage settles quicker for higher values of βkβk, since the diffusion is less apparent when the potential is high compared with the thermal energy, as discussed in the discussion of Exercise 5.

Discussion of results from 7.2¶

The plots on the left of figure 8 and 9 show the distribution of the sodium and potassium ions afer a random walk with 10001000 time steps with different cell potensials for sodium and potassium. With the dimentionless potential of βV=10βV=10, the probability of an ion travelling across the membrane is negligibly small. In the case where βVNa=10βVNa=10 and βVK=1βVK=1, as shown in figure 8, the sodium ions will be trapped on the outside of the cell, while a few of the potassium ions on the outside will be pulled into cell. Equilibrium is reached between the diffusion of potassium out of the cell and potassium transport into the cell caused by the voltage V(t)V(t), and this results in a negative voltage over the cell membrane, as shown in the plot on the right side of figure 8.

The oposite effect can be observed when βVK=10βVK=10, and βVNa=1βVNa=1, as shown in figure 9. Many sodium ions will quickly move into the cell because of both the electric voltage and the concentration gradient, while the potassium on the inside of the cell is trapped by voltage barrier. After some time, when zero potensial difference between the cell and the enviroment is reached, there is still a large concentration gradient of sodium into the cell. The concentration gradient causes the sodium to continue to diffuse into the cell until an equilibrium is reached with the sodium transportation caused by the voltage. Therefore, the voltage settles at a positive value, as shown in the plot on the right side of figure 9.

Exercise 8 - Simulating the action potential¶

Exercise 8.1¶
In [17]:
betaV0K = 50
betaV0Na = 50
t = 5000
args = randomWalkCell(L / 4, NKEnv, NNaEnv, NKCell, NNaCell, betaV0K, betaV0Na, t, pump = False, action = True)
plotRWCell(*args, betaV0K, betaV0Na, figNo = 10, smooth = True)

Discussion of results from 8.1¶

The plot on the left in figure 10 shows the particle distribution after a random walk of 10001000 time steps with an action potential. The action potenial alternates the values of the gate potentials for sodium and potassium between βV=1βV=1 and βV=50βV=50. When the voltage goes below a value of −70mV−70mV the sodium gate potential is set to βVNa=1βVNa=1 and the potassium gate potential is set to βVK=50βVK=50. When the voltage goes over a value of 30mV30mV the gate potenials switch to βVNa=50βVNa=50 and βVK=1βVK=1.

The initial concentrations of NaNa and KK result in the NaNa-gate beeing opened immediately and spiking the voltage, as seen in the plot on the right in figure 10, which shows the total voltge over time. After the initial spike, the voltage stabilizes at aproximately −35mV−35mV. Because of the random movement of potassium, the voltage can drop below −70mV−70mV and open the sodium gate causing a voltage spike. For each spike the sodium consentration inside the cell increases, resulting in a increased voltage. The increase is calculated bu running the program with 1000010000 time steps and averaging the voltage over 10001000 time steps before and after the spike. The average of five such differences is calculated to be 4mV4mV for the second spike. This decreases the probability of the voltage dropping below −70mV−70mV causing the system to stop spiking the voltage. With t=1000t=1000 time steps the voltage spikes one or two times.

It makes physical sense that this proces has to stop since the system starts in a low entropy state becouse of the concentration gradient. Every spike decreases the gradient increasing the entropy of the system. Becouse of the irreversible nature of the process no cycle can be established.

Exercise 8.2¶

In [18]:
betaV0K = 50
betaV0Na = 50
t = 5000

args = randomWalkCell(L / 4, NKEnv, NNaEnv, NKCell, NNaCell, betaV0K, betaV0Na, t, pump = True, action = True)
plotRWCell(*args, betaV0K, betaV0Na, figNo = 11, smooth = False, lineType = "-")

Discussion of results from exercise 8.2¶

The plot to the left in figure 11 shows the particle distribution after a random walk of 50005000 time steps with an action potential and with a sodium potassium pump. The action potential is the same as in Exercise 8.1. Every 10th time step the sodium potassium pump transports two potassium ions from the enviroment into the cell and three sodium ions from the cell to the enviroment. The pump transports the ions closest to the membrane, and only transports ions if there are both potassium ions and sodium ions avalilable. This ion transport results in a net charge flow to the enviroment, lowering the voltage over the membrane. This causes the voltage to drop below the action threshold of −70mV−70mV, causing action potential to spike. This results in a cyclus that will continue to run for as long as the pump runs.

The sodium potasium pump works against the concentration gradient and the electric force. This decreases the entropy of the system. This makes it possible for a cycle to be established. Because of the decrease of entropy the pump requires a supply of energy to run, which is transported by the ATP-molecule in real cells.
